WEBVTT

00:08.573 --> 00:08.791
.

00:08.834 --> 00:12.316
- Two nights after Christmas,
clear and cold

00:12.360 --> 00:14.405
an unhurried
and contented fullness

00:14.449 --> 00:18.235
had settled on a small,
quiet town in Missouri

00:18.279 --> 00:20.194
an unobtrusive little place,

00:20.237 --> 00:22.718
sort of place
that didn't make a fuss,

00:22.761 --> 00:25.373
a town called Troy.

00:25.416 --> 00:28.898
It was December 27th, 2011.

00:28.941 --> 00:31.118
There'd be a fuss tonight.

00:31.161 --> 00:34.904
Troy was about
to make headlines.

00:34.947 --> 00:38.690
The dead woman on the floor
was Betsy Faria.

00:38.734 --> 00:41.867
It was obvious that
her wrists had been slashed.

00:41.911 --> 00:46.394
The blade of a kitchen knife
was still buried in her neck.

00:46.437 --> 00:48.309
A few feet away
in the kitchen,

00:48.352 --> 00:51.399
her husband Russ
was on the phone with 911,

00:51.442 --> 00:54.315
sounding hysterical.

00:54.358 --> 00:56.578
Maybe too hysterical.

00:56.621 --> 01:01.278
- Yeah, I--I just got home
from a friend's house and--

01:01.322 --> 01:05.195
and my wife--
my wife killed herself.

01:05.239 --> 01:09.678
She's--she's--
she's on the floor.

01:09.721 --> 01:13.856
- A terrible story
too often told.

01:13.899 --> 01:17.773
Dead wife,
guilty husband feigning grief.

01:17.816 --> 01:20.776
Open and shut,
a story like that.

01:20.819 --> 01:24.258
Easy to judge the book
by its cover.

01:24.301 --> 01:26.564
You'd think what happened
on Sumac Drive

01:26.608 --> 01:29.306
was at the hands
of Russ Faria,

01:29.350 --> 01:31.743
and you'd be wrong.

01:31.787 --> 01:34.094
Dead wrong.

01:34.137 --> 01:37.662
Enter Pam Hupp.

01:37.706 --> 01:39.229
- You know, when people
want you to admit

01:39.273 --> 01:42.363
to something you didn't do?
I can't do that.

01:42.406 --> 01:45.235
I'm not that kind of person.
Mm-mm.

01:45.279 --> 01:48.282
They don't know who I am.

01:48.325 --> 01:50.197
[cheerful music]
I'm a businesswoman!

01:50.240 --> 01:52.503
I do business all the time.

01:52.547 --> 01:54.897
Flip houses, turn a profit.

01:54.940 --> 01:58.074
I'm real successful.

01:58.118 --> 02:00.381
I'm a pillar of the community.

02:00.424 --> 02:02.426
- She's a pillar
of the community.

02:02.470 --> 02:04.950
- Thanks, Ger!
Great guy.

02:04.994 --> 02:06.735
[slurps]

02:06.778 --> 02:11.131
I'm other stuff too:
a loving family woman.

02:11.174 --> 02:13.263
My husband, Mark.

02:13.307 --> 02:16.658
He thinks I'm a hoot.
- [laughs]

02:16.701 --> 02:19.095
- My son, Travis.

02:19.139 --> 02:22.142
Owns his own condo
that I financed.

02:22.185 --> 02:24.579
Sarah, from my first marriage.

02:24.622 --> 02:27.451
all: Cheese!

02:27.495 --> 02:29.714
Don't we look great?

02:29.758 --> 02:31.151
Almost forgot!

02:31.194 --> 02:33.153
My mom, Shirley.

02:33.196 --> 02:34.676
R.I.P.

02:34.719 --> 02:37.287
Took care of her
till the very end.

02:37.331 --> 02:40.160
Just like my best friend,
Betsy.

02:40.203 --> 02:42.901
Bets had a rough go
with cancer,

02:42.945 --> 02:45.643
but I got through it.

02:45.687 --> 02:47.602
I miss ya, Bets.

02:48.951 --> 02:51.562
What happened to Betsy
was hard on me too.

02:51.606 --> 02:53.999
Probably more than anyone.

02:54.043 --> 02:55.914
Except maybe Betsy.

02:55.958 --> 02:58.656
And people still say,
"Pam, she's blah, blah, blah."

02:58.700 --> 03:00.615
But everyone knows
it was her husband.

03:00.658 --> 03:02.878
Did you hear that 911 call?

03:02.921 --> 03:05.054
- [screams]

03:05.097 --> 03:07.491
[rapid breathing]

03:07.535 --> 03:09.667
- Wah-wah-wah.
What a faker.

03:09.711 --> 03:14.542
And then I get stuck
with his problems?

03:14.585 --> 03:18.589
I had to deal with her
bratty daughters, her mom--

03:18.633 --> 03:20.025
oh, my God, her mom--

03:20.069 --> 03:21.940
but I was happy to help.

03:21.984 --> 03:24.421
And here we are,

03:24.465 --> 03:27.294
all because
I was such a good friend.

03:27.337 --> 03:30.775
- Ah, the friend,
the confidant.

03:30.819 --> 03:33.038
And my, my,

03:33.082 --> 03:35.302
such a story she could tell.

03:35.345 --> 03:38.261
[sinister music]

03:38.305 --> 03:43.005
♪

03:47.270 --> 03:49.794
[line ringing]

03:49.838 --> 03:52.014
- Hello.
- Hey, how ya feeling?

03:52.057 --> 03:55.191
Want me to bring some of those
suckers when I come back?

03:55.235 --> 03:57.367
- This time, chemo wasn't bad.

03:57.411 --> 04:00.283
I feel kinda good, actually.

04:00.327 --> 04:01.850
- Great, I'm glad.

04:01.893 --> 04:05.201
I was just thinking of that
bad day a couple chemos ago.

04:05.245 --> 04:06.942
You went and played
tennis after.

04:06.985 --> 04:09.597
- Mm.
I pushed it too hard that day.

04:09.640 --> 04:11.425
- Yeah, it took like an hour

04:11.468 --> 04:13.949
to clean all the puke
off the court.

04:13.992 --> 04:16.081
Wouldn't want that going down
at your mom's.

04:16.125 --> 04:17.300
- Really, Pam.

04:17.344 --> 04:19.520
I'm good to stay.

04:19.563 --> 04:21.522
My family's here and--
- See?

04:21.565 --> 04:23.480
That's what I'm worried about.

04:23.524 --> 04:26.788
All those germs
when your white count's low.

04:26.831 --> 04:29.747
Let me feed Mark and Travis,
then I'll come pick ya up, kay?

04:29.791 --> 04:32.576
- Can I come back and get you?
- Is that Russ?

04:32.620 --> 04:35.231
He should just stay out
and play his game. I got ya.

04:35.275 --> 04:36.754
- If I wanna go home,

04:36.798 --> 04:38.800
he'll just get me
after his guys' night.

04:38.843 --> 04:42.325
- I don't mind driving.
I'll come after dinner.

04:42.369 --> 04:43.631
See how you're doing.

04:43.674 --> 04:45.807
Drink lots of water.
I'll see you soon.

04:48.288 --> 04:49.419
- Pam?

04:53.336 --> 04:55.251
- Oh, have fun
playing karate priest.

04:55.295 --> 04:58.428
- I'm a monk
with celestial powers.

05:00.212 --> 05:02.302
[bell chimes]

05:08.569 --> 05:11.615
- Oh, the mundane moments
of every day.

05:11.659 --> 05:14.052
The drinks we buy,

05:14.096 --> 05:17.142
the shops we frequent,

05:17.186 --> 05:19.449
the names
we're able to put to faces.

05:19.493 --> 05:22.322
- Oh, we're out of cherry.

05:22.365 --> 05:24.933
Ger?
- Oh.

05:24.976 --> 05:27.109
Sorry, Pam.

05:27.152 --> 05:28.458
Here you go.

05:28.502 --> 05:30.460
- Thanks.
- Uh-huh.

05:30.504 --> 05:33.463
["Jingle Bell Rock" playing]

05:33.507 --> 05:35.509
- Oh, hey, Dave.

05:35.552 --> 05:37.293
Happy late Christmas.

05:37.337 --> 05:39.730
- Hey, Pam. You too.

05:39.774 --> 05:41.253
- Thanks.

05:41.297 --> 05:42.951
Santa treat you well?
- Nah.

05:42.994 --> 05:45.214
But I wasn't that good neither.
[both chuckle]

05:45.257 --> 05:46.998
Maybe next year he'll bring
me a girlfriend, right?

05:47.042 --> 05:48.565
- You kidding?

05:48.609 --> 05:52.352
Any girl just needs to get
a look at you in that uniform.

05:52.395 --> 05:57.835
- ♪ It's the right time
to rock the night away ♪

05:57.879 --> 06:01.012
- It's the intent behind
the little things we do

06:01.056 --> 06:04.233
that says everything.
[bright chime]

06:04.276 --> 06:06.540
- This too.

06:06.583 --> 06:09.325
[sinister music]

06:09.369 --> 06:12.676
Bye.
- Bye.

06:12.720 --> 06:14.678
- It's those little things

06:14.722 --> 06:18.552
that may turn out
to prove your innocence.

06:18.595 --> 06:25.733
♪

06:29.258 --> 06:31.216
- [slurps]

06:31.260 --> 06:38.180
♪

06:44.142 --> 06:47.885
- There are things in Troy
one takes for granted.

06:47.929 --> 06:50.845
The bit of history downtown,

06:50.888 --> 06:54.414
the winter chill, and safety,

06:54.457 --> 06:57.286
but certainly not murder.

06:57.329 --> 06:59.070
[utensils scraping]

06:59.114 --> 07:02.204
[dog whining]

07:02.247 --> 07:04.206
- Those chemo rooms are tiny

07:04.249 --> 07:07.731
and there's no place to be
with all these people,

07:07.775 --> 07:10.691
so I'm stuck standing.
- On your bad leg?

07:10.734 --> 07:12.954
- All 'cause her mom's friend
Bobby's there

07:12.997 --> 07:16.348
and everyone thinks she's so
great 'cause she's from Texas

07:16.392 --> 07:18.568
like it's France or something,

07:18.612 --> 07:20.744
and I'm supposed to be
all impressed

07:20.788 --> 07:23.225
'cause that's where
Bobby's from.

07:23.268 --> 07:26.446
Now she wants Bets
to stay at her mom's tonight.

07:27.664 --> 07:29.187
- But you're still
gonna go get her?

07:29.231 --> 07:31.146
- Well, yeah.

07:32.495 --> 07:34.802
- And you're gonna call me
after you drop off Betsy?

07:34.845 --> 07:37.239
- Mm-hmm, that's my plan.

07:37.282 --> 07:39.502
[utensils scraping]

07:40.503 --> 07:42.810
[slurping]

07:42.853 --> 07:44.594
She ready?
- Pam.

07:44.638 --> 07:46.378
I didn't know
you were coming back.

07:46.422 --> 07:48.685
- Yeah, Bobby.
Bets wanted me to.

07:48.729 --> 07:50.513
She's gotta get to bed.

07:50.557 --> 07:52.080
Win-win.

07:52.123 --> 07:53.734
Now I can hear more
about Texas.

07:53.777 --> 07:57.085
All your barbecue and stuff.
- Huh.

07:57.128 --> 07:58.826
- Hey. Where's your coat?

07:58.869 --> 08:01.393
- I'm not sure where it is.

08:01.437 --> 08:04.179
- Betsy's playing her game.

08:04.222 --> 08:06.486
Why don't you just stay
for a drink?

08:06.529 --> 08:08.313
- Sure. I can chill a sec.

08:08.357 --> 08:11.316
[sinister music]

08:11.360 --> 08:15.538
♪

08:15.582 --> 08:18.193
- Oh, let me take
your coat, hmm?

08:18.236 --> 08:19.499
- No, I'm good.

08:19.542 --> 08:22.153
You play your game.

08:22.197 --> 08:25.853
♪

08:25.896 --> 08:27.681
[sniffs]

08:27.724 --> 08:32.773
♪

08:32.816 --> 08:35.210
- My berserker goes into
adrenal rage--

08:35.253 --> 08:36.820
plus three on all attacks

08:36.864 --> 08:38.822
and attacks
the Lord of Entropy.

08:38.866 --> 08:42.173
- You can't attack
the Lord of Entropy.

08:42.217 --> 08:43.218
He's a god!

08:43.261 --> 08:44.654
- Are you sure
you wanna do that?

08:44.698 --> 08:45.655
- No.
[phone vibrating]

08:45.699 --> 08:48.310
- Yes, yes, I attack.

08:48.353 --> 08:49.616
- Okay, you heard him.

08:49.659 --> 08:53.576
I mean, everybody roll
to attack.

08:53.620 --> 08:56.187
- Jackass.
[indistinct muttering]

08:56.231 --> 08:58.538
[rock music playing]

08:58.581 --> 09:00.540
- You get that.

09:00.583 --> 09:06.328
♪

09:06.371 --> 09:08.199
[exhales]

09:08.243 --> 09:11.420
[unsettling music]
- [slurping]

09:11.463 --> 09:13.074
♪

09:13.117 --> 09:15.685
- Russ took a nice photo of us
on Christmas morning.

09:15.729 --> 09:18.601
Figured out how to set
the timer and everything.

09:18.645 --> 09:22.170
[laughter]
- [slurping]

09:22.213 --> 09:23.606
- We're working on it.

09:23.650 --> 09:26.566
- I just wish that he wouldn't
smoke in the house.

09:26.609 --> 09:29.699
- With you in your condition?

09:29.743 --> 09:31.571
How's the game going?

09:31.614 --> 09:33.224
[music stops abruptly]

09:33.268 --> 09:35.575
- You know, maybe we just
go ahead and call it a night.

09:35.618 --> 09:36.880
- Wait.

09:36.924 --> 09:39.491
No, Mom, I thought
you were staying with us

09:39.535 --> 09:40.884
at Grandma's house.

09:40.928 --> 09:46.977
- Well, Pam came
all this way, so...

09:47.021 --> 09:48.500
I'll just see you
tomorrow, sweetie.

09:48.544 --> 09:50.415
- Hmm.

09:50.459 --> 09:52.896
That big beanbag is something.

09:52.940 --> 09:55.159
- Yeah, grandma got it for me
for Christmas.

09:55.203 --> 09:57.727
It's called a LoveSac.
- Mm. Hmm.

09:59.076 --> 10:01.296
- Wait, something got on it.

10:01.339 --> 10:02.732
- Yeah.

10:02.776 --> 10:05.343
I saw that when I came in.

10:05.387 --> 10:08.303
Just asking for trouble
with white.

10:09.913 --> 10:11.654
Let's get these on ya.

10:11.698 --> 10:13.830
Here.

10:14.744 --> 10:15.919
- Hey!

10:15.963 --> 10:19.314
I didn't get my hug.

10:19.357 --> 10:21.185
- We'll save it
for tomorrow, Mama.

10:21.229 --> 10:23.623
- Aww.
- Yep. See ya, Janet.

10:23.666 --> 10:26.582
[sentimental music]

10:26.626 --> 10:33.720
♪

10:36.244 --> 10:38.638
- It's hard to know
when a goodbye

10:38.681 --> 10:42.424
will turn out to be important.

10:42.467 --> 10:45.035
Who would ever think
this goodbye

10:45.079 --> 10:48.604
would turn out to be forever?

10:48.648 --> 10:53.435
♪

10:53.478 --> 10:55.393
- Whoa.

10:55.437 --> 10:57.657
You maybe wanna slow down
just a little?

10:57.700 --> 10:58.962
No rush.

10:59.006 --> 11:01.704
- Oh, was I speeding?

11:01.748 --> 11:05.142
Oops.
[chuckles]

11:05.186 --> 11:08.232
What's the opposite
of night vision?

11:08.276 --> 11:10.887
That's what I got.
[chuckles]

11:10.931 --> 11:15.065
- Yeah, I know.
Russ could've drove me.

11:15.109 --> 11:18.329
- [sniffs]

11:18.373 --> 11:21.245
Hey, let's watch a movie
at your place, huh?

11:21.289 --> 11:23.508
- [sighs]
It's been a long day, Pam.

11:23.552 --> 11:24.509
I'm tired.

11:24.553 --> 11:26.337
- Hmm.

11:26.381 --> 11:28.688
Okay.

11:28.731 --> 11:33.083
Well, just a show, then.

11:33.127 --> 11:37.914
You can't spend enough time
with the people you love.

11:37.958 --> 11:39.742
- Yeah, I know what you mean.

11:39.786 --> 11:41.701
I feel like
I don't see Mariah enough

11:41.744 --> 11:44.486
since she started
living with my mom.

11:44.529 --> 11:48.708
The school district there
is so much better.

11:48.751 --> 11:53.103
♪

11:53.147 --> 11:55.758
Well,

11:55.802 --> 11:58.761
me and the kids

11:58.805 --> 12:01.764
just wanted you to know that

12:01.808 --> 12:06.769
Russ has been so sweet.

12:06.813 --> 12:10.381
I know you're not
his biggest fan.

12:10.425 --> 12:12.775
He's a mess.

12:12.819 --> 12:17.084
Lord knows I'm a mess.

12:17.127 --> 12:20.740
That is why it is so good

12:20.783 --> 12:23.568
that you have got your eye
on us.

12:23.612 --> 12:25.962
♪

12:26.006 --> 12:29.792
And that you'll--

12:29.836 --> 12:36.581
[voice breaking]
you'll help my girls when--

12:36.625 --> 12:40.063
when--oh, God.

12:40.107 --> 12:43.240
I just don't want them
to have too hard of a time.

12:43.284 --> 12:45.416
- Here we are.

12:45.460 --> 12:50.857
♪

12:50.900 --> 12:54.469
- [sniffles]
Thanks for the ride, Pam.

12:54.512 --> 12:56.079
[lock clicks]

12:56.123 --> 12:57.777
- I promised Mark
we'd call him together

12:57.820 --> 13:00.823
when we got home.
- Oh.

13:00.867 --> 13:03.130
Is he okay?
- Yeah.

13:03.173 --> 13:05.567
Let's just call him.
[phone dialing]

13:05.610 --> 13:08.048
- Sure.

13:08.091 --> 13:12.269
- Great.
[line ringing]

13:12.313 --> 13:15.142
Hmm.

13:15.185 --> 13:16.621
- Wasn't he expecting you?

13:16.665 --> 13:18.928
- Must be away from his phone.

13:18.972 --> 13:20.103
Oh!
- Hey, it's Mark.

13:20.147 --> 13:21.235
Leave a message.
- Get ready.

13:21.278 --> 13:23.150
[line beeps]
Hey, Mark, it's us.

13:23.193 --> 13:25.848
Just got Betsy home and
she's gonna get all tucked in,

13:25.892 --> 13:29.025
but we just wanted to say hi.

13:29.069 --> 13:32.637
- Happy Christmas, Mark.
Hope you're good.

13:32.681 --> 13:34.161
Thanks for loaning me Pam.

13:34.204 --> 13:36.032
- Those little things,

13:36.076 --> 13:38.818
like a timestamped phone call,
for instance...

13:38.861 --> 13:41.951
- Perfect.
- Can make an alibi.

13:41.995 --> 13:45.041
The question is,
will it stand?

13:48.871 --> 13:49.045
.

13:49.089 --> 13:52.657
- Hello? I'm worried about ya.

13:52.701 --> 13:55.443
Bets, honestly, I don't know
why you're doing this to me.

13:55.486 --> 13:57.401
You mad or something?

13:57.445 --> 14:04.321
[dog barking]

14:04.365 --> 14:06.846
Call me. You better be okay.

14:06.889 --> 14:08.586
[dog barking]

14:08.630 --> 14:09.544
[line disconnects]

14:09.587 --> 14:15.942
[dog barking]

14:15.985 --> 14:21.904
[dog whining]

14:21.948 --> 14:24.820
[sinister music]

14:24.864 --> 14:28.911
- A phone can be
both sword and shield.

14:28.955 --> 14:32.915
Each call a strike
or a defense.

14:32.959 --> 14:39.879
♪

14:42.969 --> 14:45.841
- Janet, I've been trying Betsy
for like a half hour.

14:45.885 --> 14:48.800
No answer.
Maybe her phone's off?

14:48.844 --> 14:50.933
That's not like her, right?

14:50.977 --> 14:53.066
- No, it isn't.

14:53.109 --> 14:54.806
- Maybe she's mad at me
or something?

14:54.850 --> 14:57.157
- Oh, what would
she be mad at you for?

14:57.200 --> 14:58.636
- I don't know.

14:58.680 --> 15:01.901
She wanted to watch a movie
until Russ came home,

15:01.944 --> 15:04.077
but I said,
"You just need to rest."

15:04.120 --> 15:06.862
So she said she's gonna
watch TV till he got home

15:06.906 --> 15:10.039
and he was gonna be home in,
you know, like, an hour or so,

15:10.083 --> 15:11.345
so I said "Okay."

15:11.388 --> 15:13.564
But I would've stayed.
- Oh, God.

15:13.608 --> 15:15.958
I just hope she's not in
a bad place in her head again.

15:16.002 --> 15:17.873
- Yeah, I shouldn't
have worried ya.

15:17.917 --> 15:20.963
Just wanted to see
if maybe you knew something.

15:21.007 --> 15:22.965
I'll keep checking,

15:23.009 --> 15:25.925
[sinister music]

15:25.968 --> 15:32.932
♪

15:36.109 --> 15:39.634
- Leaving a friend's house,
do we notice the time?

15:39.677 --> 15:42.245
Should we?

15:42.289 --> 15:45.205
[unsettling music]

15:45.248 --> 15:52.299
♪

15:52.342 --> 15:55.476
It's a funny thing, fate.

15:55.519 --> 15:57.913
All just a series
of decisions.

15:57.957 --> 16:01.003
Right or left, stay or go.

16:01.047 --> 16:02.874
- Welcome to Arby's. What can
I get for you tonight?

16:02.918 --> 16:06.182
- Um...
[clears throat]

16:06.226 --> 16:09.490
I'll have the, uh,
chicken bacon Swiss.

16:09.533 --> 16:12.058
Uh, sorry, no.

16:12.101 --> 16:14.886
I'll have
the beef and cheddar melt.

16:14.930 --> 16:16.410
- Sometimes one small thing

16:16.453 --> 16:18.890
could make all the difference
in the world.

16:18.934 --> 16:21.241
Sometimes
it's stopping at a light

16:21.284 --> 16:24.070
before a truck barrels through
the intersection.

16:24.113 --> 16:27.247
- Actually,
two beef and cheddars.

16:27.290 --> 16:30.076
- Other times,
it's how to satisfy

16:30.119 --> 16:32.600
a case of the munchies.

16:32.643 --> 16:35.168
[rock music playing]

16:35.211 --> 16:37.518
- Oh, thank you.

16:37.561 --> 16:44.525
♪

16:44.568 --> 16:47.528
[dramatic music]

16:47.571 --> 16:54.665
♪

17:06.677 --> 17:10.812
[dog whining]
- Hey, girl.

17:10.855 --> 17:13.119
Why you out here, huh?

17:13.162 --> 17:15.295
Come on.

17:15.338 --> 17:20.300
♪

17:20.343 --> 17:21.910
[screams]

17:21.953 --> 17:24.391
- Lincoln County 911.
What's your emergency?

17:24.434 --> 17:26.436
- [sniffles]
Hello?

17:26.480 --> 17:28.873
- Ma'am, I'm gonna need you to
take a couple of deep breaths.

17:28.917 --> 17:30.614
What's your name?

17:30.658 --> 17:35.097
- [sobbing] My name--
my name is Russell Faria.

17:35.141 --> 17:38.187
- Okay, Russell, what is
the address where you are?

17:38.231 --> 17:43.888
- 1--1--130 Sumac.

17:43.932 --> 17:47.153
[sobbing]

17:47.196 --> 17:51.461
I--I just got home
from a friend's house, and--

17:51.505 --> 17:53.637
and my wife--

17:53.681 --> 17:55.639
my wife killed herself.

17:55.683 --> 17:59.774
She's--she's--
she's on the floor.

17:59.817 --> 18:01.036
- O--okay, Russell,

18:01.080 --> 18:03.560
I need you to calm down,
honey, okay?

18:03.604 --> 18:05.519
What did she do? Do you know?

18:05.562 --> 18:08.348
- She's got a knife in her neck

18:08.391 --> 18:10.045
and she sliced her arms.

18:10.089 --> 18:12.743
- Okay.
Is she breathing at all?

18:12.787 --> 18:17.183
- She's dead.
[rapid shallow breathing]

18:17.226 --> 18:19.663
- The worst call
he ever had to make,

18:19.707 --> 18:21.274
and Russ had no idea

18:21.317 --> 18:24.103
how much it would be
picked apart.

18:26.540 --> 18:26.714
.

18:26.757 --> 18:28.846
- [breathing heavily]

18:28.890 --> 18:30.500
- Russell,
they're on their way, hon.

18:30.544 --> 18:32.763
Okay, is there anybody else
in the house?

18:32.807 --> 18:34.200
- [voice breaking]
No.

18:34.243 --> 18:36.811
No, I'm all alone.

18:36.854 --> 18:39.248
[sirens wailing]

18:39.292 --> 18:40.728
- Russell,
I've got a couple of officers

18:40.771 --> 18:42.208
out there right now.

18:42.251 --> 18:44.035
Can you do me a favor
and open your front door?

18:44.079 --> 18:47.909
- [grunts]

18:47.952 --> 18:50.085
[pounding on door]

18:50.129 --> 18:53.132
- Sheriff's department.

18:55.438 --> 18:57.484
- Sir, is there anyone else
in the house?

18:57.527 --> 18:59.486
- No.

18:59.529 --> 19:01.009
- You said your wife
killed herself?

19:01.052 --> 19:02.184
- Yes.

19:02.228 --> 19:04.882
Oh, my God, Betsy.

19:04.926 --> 19:09.409
[sobbing]

19:09.452 --> 19:10.888
- Could you please
take him outside?

19:10.932 --> 19:14.370
- [sobbing]

19:14.414 --> 19:17.591
[soft tense music]

19:17.634 --> 19:18.679
♪

19:18.722 --> 19:21.334
- Got a female down
at 130 Sumac.

19:21.377 --> 19:23.640
Looks to be a definite J4.

19:23.684 --> 19:25.599
- Copy that.

19:25.642 --> 19:32.562
[sirens wailing]

19:32.606 --> 19:36.218
- Update information
at crime scene, 130 Sumac.

19:36.262 --> 19:40.570
[indistinct chatter]

19:40.614 --> 19:42.224
- I'm just gonna get this
off of you.

19:42.268 --> 19:43.573
- No witnesses as of yet.

19:43.617 --> 19:45.009
County's sweeping
the neighborhood now

19:45.053 --> 19:47.055
to see if anybody
saw or heard anything.

19:47.098 --> 19:49.231
- [shivers]

19:49.275 --> 19:52.234
[desolate music]

19:52.278 --> 19:56.934
♪

19:56.978 --> 19:59.110
- It was 34 degrees in Troy

19:59.154 --> 20:03.114
when Detective Michael Merkel
took Russ' coat for evidence.

20:03.158 --> 20:06.205
[dog barking]

20:06.248 --> 20:07.989
Russ' beloved dog, Cicely,

20:08.032 --> 20:10.905
had been mysteriously
left outside the house.

20:10.948 --> 20:13.603
While inside,
Captain Mike Lang

20:13.647 --> 20:17.259
and lead detective
Ryan McCarrick got to work.

20:17.303 --> 20:19.130
[dramatic music]

20:19.174 --> 20:21.002
- See the sock hanging off?

20:21.045 --> 20:22.351
- Signs of a struggle.

20:22.395 --> 20:24.135
- And the knife in her neck?

20:24.179 --> 20:25.920
Doesn't spell suicide.

20:25.963 --> 20:28.923
You hear that 911 call?
- Totally over the top.

20:28.966 --> 20:30.794
- We need to know everything
this guy touched

20:30.838 --> 20:32.622
in the last 24 hours.

20:32.666 --> 20:34.755
The scene will never be
as fresh as it is right now.

20:34.798 --> 20:36.626
- Here's one for ya.
I didn't see a drop of blood

20:36.670 --> 20:37.801
anywhere on him.

20:37.845 --> 20:39.063
Must've washed it off.

20:39.107 --> 20:40.456
- Check every inch
of the bathrooms.

20:40.500 --> 20:43.285
Showers, laundry.
Find where he washed it off.

20:43.329 --> 20:50.205
♪

20:50.249 --> 20:52.816
Hey, this pillow's
in a weird spot.

20:52.860 --> 20:55.602
[camera snaps]

20:55.645 --> 20:58.344
[indistinct radio chatter]

20:58.387 --> 20:59.649
- Where am I going?

20:59.693 --> 21:00.824
- We just need you
to come down the station,

21:00.868 --> 21:03.262
answer some questions
about your wife.

21:03.305 --> 21:05.176
Due diligence.

21:05.220 --> 21:12.314
♪

21:18.973 --> 21:23.151
[siren wailing]

21:23.194 --> 21:24.413
- How you liking
your first murder?

21:24.457 --> 21:26.023
- Honestly, thought it'd
be harder to solve.

21:26.067 --> 21:28.504
- We got statistics
for a reason, brother.

21:28.548 --> 21:31.115
Learned that in my 200 hours
of training.

21:31.159 --> 21:32.508
This?

21:32.552 --> 21:35.468
Textbook spousal homicide.

21:35.511 --> 21:38.035
- The drive to Betsy's
was fine.

21:38.079 --> 21:42.257
Oh, my God, Mark, Janet got
Mariah this ginormous beanbag.

21:42.301 --> 21:43.867
The size of a house.

21:43.911 --> 21:45.782
Called a "love suck"
or something?

21:45.826 --> 21:49.177
Those things cost,
like, a $1,000.

21:49.220 --> 21:52.398
If I had beanbag money
like that

21:52.441 --> 21:56.576
when I was her age,
I'd have gone to college.

21:56.619 --> 21:58.229
[gasps]

21:58.273 --> 22:01.363
Ugh!

22:01.407 --> 22:02.364
Burned it.

22:02.408 --> 22:05.367
[unsettling music]

22:05.411 --> 22:12.548
♪

22:20.643 --> 22:22.732
- So, Russ, tell me about
you and Betsy.

22:22.776 --> 22:25.953
And you've been married
how long?

22:25.996 --> 22:28.390
- 12 years.

22:28.434 --> 22:31.306
- 12 years.
That's a long time.

22:31.350 --> 22:33.395
You know, I know marriages
can get messy.

22:33.439 --> 22:35.919
You two had any problems?

22:35.963 --> 22:37.399
- We had our bumps.

22:37.443 --> 22:39.401
We were separated.

22:39.445 --> 22:41.621
Didn't get along for a bit
but then we--

22:41.664 --> 22:45.973
we found this new church
and we worked it out.

22:46.016 --> 22:48.845
- Yeah?
What's your pastor's name?

22:48.889 --> 22:49.890
- Mike Shriner.

22:49.933 --> 22:52.371
- You go to Morningstar?

22:52.414 --> 22:53.807
- You know Mike?

22:53.850 --> 22:57.114
- I know Pastor Mike.
Great guy.

22:57.158 --> 22:58.681
- He's a good friend.

22:58.725 --> 22:59.987
- And everything
with the family's

23:00.030 --> 23:01.380
been good since then?

23:01.423 --> 23:06.385
- Well, uh, normal stuff.

23:06.428 --> 23:07.864
We found out our daughter Lily

23:07.908 --> 23:10.301
stole some money
from Betsy's mom.

23:10.345 --> 23:12.129
There's always something.

23:12.173 --> 23:14.828
- Right. Always something.

23:14.871 --> 23:16.960
And she was sick?

23:17.004 --> 23:18.527
Depressed?

23:18.571 --> 23:20.137
Enough to kill herself?

23:20.181 --> 23:22.792
- She had cancer.

23:22.836 --> 23:25.142
We thought she got rid of it.

23:25.186 --> 23:29.103
She had a mastectomy,
but it spread to her liver.

23:29.146 --> 23:30.626
Now it's in her liver

23:30.670 --> 23:34.717
even though she had
her whole boob removed.

23:34.761 --> 23:37.198
Am I allowed
to go to the bathroom?

23:37.241 --> 23:39.330
- Look at him and decide:

23:39.374 --> 23:42.072
do you see a killer?

23:42.116 --> 23:46.468
DA Leah Askey was about
to decide for herself.

23:46.512 --> 23:49.079
- [sighs]
- Hey.

23:49.123 --> 23:50.429
Just wait till you hear this.

23:50.472 --> 23:51.821
- I thought I told you
not to call me this late.

23:51.865 --> 23:52.996
What if I was home with Chris?

23:53.040 --> 23:55.216
- Yeah, but there's
been a murder.

23:55.259 --> 23:57.827
A homicide, like, a big one.

23:57.871 --> 23:59.263
- Okay. And?

23:59.307 --> 24:01.004
- Some lady on Sumac
got stabbed,

24:01.048 --> 24:03.529
I don't know, 20,

24:03.572 --> 24:05.487
maybe 60 times.

24:05.531 --> 24:07.054
I processed
the crime scene myself

24:07.097 --> 24:10.884
and, uh,
we have the husband here now.

24:10.927 --> 24:13.060
- I'll be there
first thing in the morning.

24:13.103 --> 24:16.280
You Miranded him, right?

24:16.324 --> 24:17.760
- Oh, yeah.

24:17.804 --> 24:19.022
Yeah.

24:19.066 --> 24:20.546
You know, hold on one second
for me, okay?

24:20.589 --> 24:21.677
Just hold on one second.

24:21.721 --> 24:23.462
[determined music]

24:23.505 --> 24:25.202
- [grunts]
- Sorry.

24:25.246 --> 24:28.510
- Russ, how 'bout we make this
easier on both of us,

24:28.554 --> 24:30.381
'cause my patience is--

24:30.425 --> 24:35.909
♪

24:35.952 --> 24:41.218
Sit tight.

24:41.262 --> 24:44.221
- Oh, my God.
Why would she do this to me?

24:44.265 --> 24:47.137
♪

24:47.181 --> 24:49.139
- Hey.
Sorry about that.

24:49.183 --> 24:52.534
You know, so much to do
and not enough bodies.

24:52.578 --> 24:55.319
Um, look, somehow--

24:55.363 --> 24:58.540
and bear with me, it's--
it's been a long day, but--

24:58.584 --> 25:00.586
you know, when we bring someone
in here to talk like this,

25:00.629 --> 25:03.284
we gotta run through
their rights with them

25:03.327 --> 25:04.851
and somehow I forgot, okay?

25:04.894 --> 25:07.462
So I'm just gonna run
over this with you real quick.

25:07.506 --> 25:09.899
Right, you have the right
to remain silent.

25:09.943 --> 25:11.814
Anything you say can and will
be used against you

25:11.858 --> 25:14.121
in a court of law--
- Am I being arrested?

25:14.164 --> 25:15.905
- We're just trying
to find out what happened

25:15.949 --> 25:17.646
and you've given us
great information.

25:17.690 --> 25:20.997
- But do I need a lawyer?

25:21.041 --> 25:23.522
- Only if you did
something wrong.

25:25.436 --> 25:27.569
Okay, then.

25:27.613 --> 25:31.530
- Do you think I could
get another blanket?

25:31.573 --> 25:34.533
[unsettling music]

25:34.576 --> 25:41.627
♪

25:43.193 --> 25:47.458
[phone ringing]

25:47.502 --> 25:50.810
♪

25:50.853 --> 25:52.638
- Hello?

25:52.681 --> 25:54.465
♪

25:54.509 --> 25:56.642
Oh, my God, what happened?

25:56.685 --> 25:58.687
♪

25:58.731 --> 26:01.647
Sure, officer,
thanks for the heads-up.

26:01.690 --> 26:03.605
♪

26:03.649 --> 26:07.957
Well, my husband is working,
but I'll be here.

26:08.001 --> 26:10.003
Thanks.

26:10.046 --> 26:16.052
♪

26:19.708 --> 26:22.624
[unsettling music]

26:22.668 --> 26:28.761
♪

26:28.804 --> 26:30.893
- Oh.

26:30.937 --> 26:37.857
♪

26:37.900 --> 26:40.120
[doorbell rings]

26:40.163 --> 26:47.127
♪

26:47.170 --> 26:48.650
- [sniffs]

26:48.694 --> 26:55.614
♪

26:57.833 --> 27:00.314
- Hi. Come in.

27:00.357 --> 27:02.446
I've just been so upset.

27:02.490 --> 27:03.534
- Sorry.

27:03.578 --> 27:05.798
Did we catch you at a bad time?

27:05.841 --> 27:07.538
Do you need a second to change?

27:07.582 --> 27:08.801
- No, I'm good.

27:08.844 --> 27:10.716
And now's perfect.

27:13.849 --> 27:15.634
Can I get you anything?

27:15.677 --> 27:18.506
Coffee?
- No, thanks, we're okay.

27:18.549 --> 27:19.986
Thanks for making the time,
Ms. Hupp.

27:20.029 --> 27:21.161
- Of course.

27:21.204 --> 27:23.337
I just can't believe it.

27:23.380 --> 27:26.732
You can, um, sit anywhere.
[dog whines]

27:26.775 --> 27:29.212
So what happened to Betsy?

27:29.256 --> 27:31.519
Some kind of accident
or something?

27:31.562 --> 27:35.131
- No, she's not
accidentally dead.

27:35.175 --> 27:37.786
She's not naturally dead.

27:37.830 --> 27:38.831
- What's that mean?

27:38.874 --> 27:40.006
- It's an active investigation

27:40.049 --> 27:41.181
so we can't say much,

27:41.224 --> 27:43.836
but we're trying
to figure that out.

27:43.879 --> 27:45.185
- Oh.

27:45.228 --> 27:47.100
- We both know
the suicide thing is crazy.

27:47.143 --> 27:50.581
They've found 52 stab wounds
on her so far.

27:50.625 --> 27:52.409
- No.

27:52.453 --> 27:53.280
No.

27:53.323 --> 27:54.455
- Yeah.
- No!

27:54.498 --> 27:56.196
- They haven't been able
to stop counting.

27:56.239 --> 27:58.024
You're not gonna convince us
it was a suicide.

27:58.067 --> 28:01.505
- Betsy! No.
[sobs]

28:01.549 --> 28:04.030
- The truth will come out.
- [sniffles]

28:04.073 --> 28:05.074
The truth?

28:05.118 --> 28:06.554
- Yeah, and this huge weight

28:06.597 --> 28:08.643
will be lifted
off your shoulders.

28:08.687 --> 28:10.645
- What?

28:10.689 --> 28:14.301
You mean--

28:14.344 --> 28:15.737
I didn't do this.

28:15.781 --> 28:17.783
- [sighs]
All right. It's okay, bud.

28:17.826 --> 28:21.395
Look, let's go over
your story so far.

28:21.438 --> 28:22.657
You said you didn't
take Betsy home,

28:22.701 --> 28:24.528
that someone dropped her off,
right?

28:24.572 --> 28:26.400
Who was that?
- Her friend Pam.

28:26.443 --> 28:28.576
She's been helping us out
with Betsy.

28:28.619 --> 28:30.447
- Okay.
You mind spelling that for me?

28:30.491 --> 28:32.493
- H-U--

28:32.536 --> 28:34.495
- P-P.

28:34.538 --> 28:36.932
Um, it's a homeless shelter,

28:36.976 --> 28:39.500
battered women in a church. -
Oh, that's so nice.

28:39.543 --> 28:41.023
- So that's my Tuesday nights

28:41.067 --> 28:44.374
and Bets always likes to, um,
help those women with me,

28:44.418 --> 28:45.636
bring them dinner, you know.

28:45.680 --> 28:48.465
[dog whines]
I know, honey.

28:48.509 --> 28:49.728
The husbands aren't cooking,

28:49.771 --> 28:51.512
being they're battered
and everything.

28:51.555 --> 28:53.427
- Right.
- So from there,

28:53.470 --> 28:55.168
I go straight to my mom's.

28:55.211 --> 28:57.431
She's going through
Alzheimer's.

28:57.474 --> 28:58.606
She doesn't know
what she's saying

28:58.649 --> 29:00.173
or where she is half the time.

29:00.216 --> 29:01.565
- That must be hard.

29:01.609 --> 29:04.264
- Oh, it is.

29:04.307 --> 29:05.787
And on top of all of that,

29:05.831 --> 29:07.571
I'm driving to Betsy
to all her appointments.

29:07.615 --> 29:10.183
She's got chemo, whatnot,
all her scans,

29:10.226 --> 29:12.576
but her family's
real appreciative.

29:12.620 --> 29:15.536
Her friends were worried
about her.

29:15.579 --> 29:17.625
- It would help if you could
tell us more about last night.

29:17.668 --> 29:20.671
You said you got back
to Betsy's at 6:30 p.m.?

29:20.715 --> 29:21.716
- Yes.

29:21.760 --> 29:24.719
[dramatic music]

29:24.763 --> 29:26.808
♪

29:26.852 --> 29:28.636
Here we are.

29:28.679 --> 29:32.640
We left my husband a voicemail
when we got there.

29:32.683 --> 29:37.427
So he should have that
on his phone.

29:37.471 --> 29:39.125
You could ask him.

29:39.168 --> 29:40.256
- You called from
inside the house?

29:40.300 --> 29:41.910
- No, no, from the car.

29:41.954 --> 29:44.870
- Right. And then you just
dropped her outside and left?

29:44.913 --> 29:46.262
- Correct.

29:46.306 --> 29:48.482
- [sniffles]

29:48.525 --> 29:50.136
Thanks for the ride, Pam.

29:50.179 --> 29:52.181
- She was tired
from the chemo.

29:52.225 --> 29:54.357
She puked
her guts out earlier.

29:54.401 --> 29:56.795
Sweet dreams.

29:57.578 --> 29:59.101
I always bring suckers
in my bag

29:59.145 --> 30:01.974
to help her with the nausea.

30:02.017 --> 30:04.324
♪

30:04.367 --> 30:06.108
- But it must have been
a little later than 6:30.

30:06.152 --> 30:08.023
The drive is what, a half hour?

30:08.067 --> 30:10.852
- [sniffles]

30:10.896 --> 30:14.682
Um...

30:14.725 --> 30:15.944
I'm so sorry.

30:15.988 --> 30:17.685
[chuckles]

30:17.728 --> 30:19.818
My brain gets
kind of funny sometimes.

30:19.861 --> 30:20.949
I get mixed up.

30:20.993 --> 30:22.342
- It's all right.
Sorry to hear that.

30:22.385 --> 30:24.126
- I had an accident at work.

30:24.170 --> 30:25.693
You know, we were
moving the office

30:25.736 --> 30:27.303
and there were boxes
laying around

30:27.347 --> 30:29.871
and I tripped and
I fell into a filing cabinet.

30:29.915 --> 30:31.438
Blah, blah, blah.

30:31.481 --> 30:34.006
You know, got knocked out,
had to have back surgery.

30:34.049 --> 30:36.443
- Wow. How's your head?

30:36.486 --> 30:38.532
Your memory, I mean.

30:38.575 --> 30:39.620
- Great.

30:39.663 --> 30:40.882
I have to remember everything

30:40.926 --> 30:44.103
for an entire house,
basically, so--

30:44.146 --> 30:46.453
- Mm.
- Hmm.

30:46.496 --> 30:48.194
So we were in the driveway,

30:48.237 --> 30:49.717
chit-chatted for a few...

30:49.760 --> 30:52.198
- Would you say it was
less than ten minutes?

30:52.241 --> 30:54.069
- Gosh, I don't--I don't know.

30:54.113 --> 30:57.029
I don't know. I'm not sure.

30:57.072 --> 30:58.334
I don't remember.

30:58.378 --> 31:00.206
- Between 10 and 20?

31:00.249 --> 31:02.425
- Um, could've been, yeah.

31:05.602 --> 31:07.691
Wasn't paying attention though.

31:07.735 --> 31:09.998
I was just trying to get
out of there

31:10.042 --> 31:12.044
'cause with Betsy, you know--

31:12.087 --> 31:13.175
[vocalizes]

31:13.219 --> 31:17.136
♪

31:17.179 --> 31:18.267
Here we are.

31:18.311 --> 31:20.617
- Oh, thanks for the ride, Pam.

31:20.661 --> 31:25.535
- Girl, anything for my best
friend in the entire world.

31:25.579 --> 31:27.233
- I wish I could
just stay with you.

31:27.276 --> 31:28.364
- Girls' night!

31:28.408 --> 31:30.018
- Girls' night forever!

31:30.062 --> 31:36.590
[both laugh]

31:36.633 --> 31:41.551
- She said she didn't have
clothes or anything with her.

31:41.595 --> 31:45.338
She was at her mom's,
I guess, all weekend.

31:45.381 --> 31:46.426
- How come she was staying
at her mom's

31:46.469 --> 31:48.080
and not at Sumac Drive?

31:48.123 --> 31:50.038
- That's Russ' house.

31:50.082 --> 31:52.693
He wouldn't let her
put her name on the title.

31:52.736 --> 31:54.956
- Okay, but do you know
why she'd stay at her mom's?

31:55.000 --> 31:58.264
- A lot of it was
she didn't like to drive,

31:58.307 --> 32:02.268
and a lot of it was, um,

32:02.311 --> 32:03.791
she didn't wanna go home.

32:03.834 --> 32:06.141
- Pam and Betsy
hang out sometimes.

32:06.185 --> 32:08.927
She likes talking to Pam.

32:08.970 --> 32:11.625
Pam is a good person.

32:11.668 --> 32:13.322
- So were they currently
separated

32:13.366 --> 32:15.020
and having issues or--

32:15.063 --> 32:16.282
- Not right now.

32:16.325 --> 32:18.675
I mean,
but that would change a lot.

32:18.719 --> 32:21.635
They were separated,
gosh, six or seven times

32:21.678 --> 32:24.290
off and on through the years.

32:24.333 --> 32:26.118
He does a lot of pot.

32:26.161 --> 32:27.336
And he smokes in the house,

32:27.380 --> 32:29.904
even with her cancer and all.

32:29.948 --> 32:30.905
Mm-hmm.

32:30.949 --> 32:33.734
And his temper.
[scoffs quietly]

32:33.777 --> 32:36.693
That's how come Mariah
moved in with Betsy's mom.

32:36.737 --> 32:38.652
[sniffs]

32:38.695 --> 32:40.697
- Was he ever violent
with Betsy?

32:40.741 --> 32:42.656
- I was at their place a lot.

32:42.699 --> 32:45.311
And, um, he's not--

32:45.354 --> 32:48.836
he's not the most, um--

32:48.879 --> 32:55.016
he was kinda not nice
verbally to her.

32:55.060 --> 32:58.063
Mm.

32:58.106 --> 33:00.195
You know the type.

33:00.239 --> 33:02.719
Real aggressive.

33:02.763 --> 33:05.026
[in baby-talk]
He's a pusher. He's a pusher.

33:05.070 --> 33:08.247
And I just don't care
for his type.

33:08.290 --> 33:10.162
- Do you remember if Russ' car
was in the driveway

33:10.205 --> 33:12.599
when you arrived?
- Uh, yeah.

33:12.642 --> 33:14.644
Here we are.

33:14.688 --> 33:18.083
- Thanks for the ride, Pam.

33:18.126 --> 33:20.041
Oh, good, Russ is home.

33:20.085 --> 33:22.348
- Looks like it.

33:22.391 --> 33:23.871
- And did you go inside at all?

33:23.914 --> 33:28.049
- For a bit.
- She said she didn't go in.

33:28.093 --> 33:29.572
- Betsy asked me to.

33:29.616 --> 33:32.532
Um, and, um,
she wanted to watch TV,

33:32.575 --> 33:34.621
but, um,
I was just trying to go.

33:34.664 --> 33:36.492
- Were the lights on inside?

33:36.536 --> 33:38.016
- No.

33:38.059 --> 33:40.366
- The house was dark even
though Russ' car was there?

33:40.409 --> 33:44.239
- Um, Russ' car was there

33:44.283 --> 33:47.590
and the lights were off,

33:47.634 --> 33:51.029
which we thought
was kind of weird.

33:51.072 --> 33:53.205
But then she goes--
uh, she goes,

33:53.248 --> 33:54.641
"Oh, well, Russ is home.

33:54.684 --> 33:56.773
And he left the door
unlocked for me."

33:56.817 --> 34:00.255
And I said, "Well, I better
walk you to the door.

34:00.299 --> 34:02.431
♪

34:02.475 --> 34:04.433
She had a bag,
blah, blah, blah,

34:04.477 --> 34:05.913
stuff like that.

34:05.956 --> 34:08.176
Uh, so I walked to the door
and in for just a bit,

34:08.220 --> 34:10.352
till she could get a light on.
- And could you see--

34:10.396 --> 34:14.400
- And then we had to put her
dog out in the yard

34:14.443 --> 34:16.924
'cause he was so annoying.

34:16.967 --> 34:18.186
Aggressive.

34:18.230 --> 34:21.059
I love dogs.

34:21.102 --> 34:23.061
Big dog fan.

34:23.104 --> 34:25.759
[in baby-talk]
But I just hate that type.

34:25.802 --> 34:27.935
- And then you left?
- Yes.

34:27.978 --> 34:29.458
And then I called Betsy
to make sure

34:29.502 --> 34:31.417
she got to bed okay.

34:31.460 --> 34:33.419
- Could we see your phone?

34:33.462 --> 34:34.811
♪

34:34.855 --> 34:36.639
- Mm-hmm.

34:36.683 --> 34:39.077
♪

34:39.120 --> 34:40.600
Does Betsy's family know?

34:40.643 --> 34:42.341
- Yes, they've been informed.

34:42.384 --> 34:44.386
- Mm.

34:44.430 --> 34:46.388
[phone beeping]

34:46.432 --> 34:48.303
- Yeah, see?

34:48.347 --> 34:49.478
Called her when I got home.

34:49.522 --> 34:51.393
- You were home
when you called her?

34:51.437 --> 34:52.873
- Yep.

34:52.916 --> 34:54.657
Betsy knew I don't see
in the dark

34:54.701 --> 34:57.399
and she wanted me to check in.

34:57.443 --> 35:01.142
And then I ate something,

35:01.186 --> 35:03.623
a piece of pie, whatever,

35:03.666 --> 35:06.060
and then I went
and got a shower

35:06.104 --> 35:10.325
and then I called her mom.
[sucks lips]

35:10.369 --> 35:15.852
♪

35:15.896 --> 35:18.812
You know what you should
look for is--

35:18.855 --> 35:21.293
is there was this letter

35:21.336 --> 35:25.253
that Bets was gonna send to me

35:25.297 --> 35:29.649
about Russ
putting a pillow over her face.

35:29.692 --> 35:31.999
- A pillow?
- Yeah.

35:32.042 --> 35:34.001
Russ started playing this game

35:34.044 --> 35:37.091
of putting a pillow
over her face, um,

35:37.135 --> 35:38.832
just to see
what it would feel like.

35:38.875 --> 35:40.007
I don't know if he said,

35:40.050 --> 35:41.313
"This is what it's
gonna feel like

35:41.356 --> 35:43.706
when you die or whatever,"

35:43.750 --> 35:46.535
and then act like
he was kidding.

35:46.579 --> 35:48.189
Yeah.

35:48.233 --> 35:50.844
I didn't really know him
that well though.

35:50.887 --> 35:54.543
I just met him about
three times in ten years.

35:54.587 --> 35:57.198
[dog whining]
Yeah.

35:57.242 --> 35:59.200
- Hm.

35:59.244 --> 36:01.724
♪

36:01.768 --> 36:06.555
- Yeah, I didn't--
I didn't know him very well.

36:06.599 --> 36:07.774
[sniffs]

36:11.386 --> 36:13.388
- I could not do this.
- Look, buddy.

36:13.432 --> 36:15.129
We're past it, okay?
We're past it.

36:15.173 --> 36:17.000
There's too much evidence here,
Russ.

36:17.044 --> 36:19.438
And hey, being, you know--

36:19.481 --> 36:22.136
being honest,
you're a church-going man.

36:22.180 --> 36:23.746
You're a church-going man?

36:23.790 --> 36:24.878
- Yes.
- Yeah.

36:24.921 --> 36:26.314
- Think of Pastor Mike.

36:26.358 --> 36:27.576
Think what he would say.

36:27.620 --> 36:29.230
- He'd believe
I didn't do this.

36:29.274 --> 36:30.449
- And what about God?

36:30.492 --> 36:31.667
God's in this room with us
right now.

36:31.711 --> 36:33.843
- And God knows
that I did not do this.

36:33.887 --> 36:35.280
I could not do this.

36:35.323 --> 36:37.325
I found her like that
when I got home.

36:37.369 --> 36:40.067
- We're lied to all the time,
but God,

36:40.110 --> 36:42.896
God knows the truth.

36:42.939 --> 36:45.681
- Oh, officers?

36:45.725 --> 36:49.207
Since you're asking me
so much about Russ,

36:49.250 --> 36:50.686
should I be worried?

36:50.730 --> 36:52.732
- No, ma'am, we're keeping him
at the station.

36:55.300 --> 36:58.128
- They say there's
no right way to grieve.

36:58.172 --> 36:59.869
- Pam.

36:59.913 --> 37:02.220
Pam, what's going on?

37:02.263 --> 37:04.004
What are the police doing here?

37:04.047 --> 37:07.007
- Something happened, Minnie.
Something terrible.

37:07.050 --> 37:08.008
I'll tell you about it later.

37:08.051 --> 37:11.838
I gotta go someplace.

37:11.881 --> 37:15.233
- Some of us may cry
in times like these,

37:15.276 --> 37:18.323
while others get busy.

37:18.366 --> 37:21.282
[determined music]

37:21.326 --> 37:25.199
♪

37:25.243 --> 37:31.379
- [sobbing]

37:31.423 --> 37:33.251
- He'll break. Not worried.

37:33.294 --> 37:36.732
- [sobbing]

37:36.776 --> 37:38.691
- You were promoted
to Homicide supervisor,

37:38.734 --> 37:40.606
what, a month ago?

37:40.649 --> 37:41.824
- Six months ago.

37:41.868 --> 37:43.609
- It shows.

37:43.652 --> 37:46.699
- [sobbing]

37:46.742 --> 37:49.702
- You think after that 911 call
he'd run out of tears.

37:49.745 --> 37:52.487
Where's the autopsy report?
- Almost done.

37:52.531 --> 37:55.621
More than 50 stab wounds.
It screams crime of passion.

37:55.664 --> 37:58.145
- Yeah, we got a lot of info
from her best friend.

37:58.188 --> 37:59.494
She dropped her off
right before.

37:59.538 --> 38:01.801
Said the guy's
got a real temper.

38:01.844 --> 38:04.934
I mean, who else would do that
to a woman dying of cancer?

38:04.978 --> 38:06.762
- [sobbing]

38:06.806 --> 38:09.548
- And he still hasn't asked
for a lawyer?

38:09.591 --> 38:11.376
- Loser doesn't even know
he needs one.

38:11.419 --> 38:14.335
[unsettling music]

38:14.379 --> 38:21.473
♪

38:33.746 --> 38:35.878
- [slurping]

38:40.709 --> 38:41.841
[bell chimes]

38:44.060 --> 38:51.198
♪

39:00.120 --> 39:01.730
[exhales]

39:01.774 --> 39:08.694
♪

39:15.091 --> 39:18.225
[knocking on door]

39:19.574 --> 39:21.010
Janet.

39:21.054 --> 39:23.361
Gosh.

39:23.404 --> 39:27.190
I don't know what to say.

39:27.234 --> 39:29.323
I got--I got you this.

39:29.367 --> 39:32.065
It made me think of Betsy.

39:32.108 --> 39:35.721
You know, her heart.

39:35.764 --> 39:38.898
♪

39:38.941 --> 39:42.423
I have one just like it.

39:42.467 --> 39:44.686
- Who would do this?

39:44.730 --> 39:47.602
To Betsy?

39:47.646 --> 39:50.344
- Well, they're holding Russ,
aren't they?

39:50.388 --> 39:52.781
- Russ?
- Yeah.

39:52.825 --> 39:54.522
Police were asking
all about him.

39:54.566 --> 39:56.524
Is he violent?
Did he get verbal at her?

39:56.568 --> 39:58.047
All that kinda stuff.

39:58.091 --> 39:59.875
- Russ wouldn't have--

39:59.919 --> 40:04.489
- They still have him
down at the station, you know?

40:04.532 --> 40:06.621
Doesn't look good.

40:10.451 --> 40:12.845
Well, you gonna let me in?

40:12.888 --> 40:14.063
♪

40:14.107 --> 40:16.239
Or if it's just family--

40:16.283 --> 40:18.416
I--I drove all the way here,

40:18.459 --> 40:22.245
but I--I can go.
- No, come in.

40:22.289 --> 40:23.377
[sighs]

40:23.421 --> 40:25.335
You're family, Pam.

40:25.379 --> 40:27.381
- She's family.
She's there for you.

40:27.425 --> 40:28.730
She's your neighbor.

40:28.774 --> 40:31.516
She's your friend from church.

40:31.559 --> 40:34.475
She's the one
you never see coming.

40:34.519 --> 40:38.348
But that's the thing
about Pam.

40:40.699 --> 40:40.916
.

40:40.960 --> 40:44.703
- Did you kill Betsy Faria?

40:44.746 --> 40:46.531
- No.

40:46.574 --> 40:48.315
- You boys want a cookie?

40:48.358 --> 40:49.534
- So I take it
you knew Russell Faria.

40:49.577 --> 40:52.058
- I didn't really know the guy,

40:52.101 --> 40:54.539
but he seemed sorta...

40:54.582 --> 40:57.280
- Abusive?
- Real abusive.

40:57.324 --> 40:58.412
- That's Joel Schwartz.

40:58.456 --> 41:00.240
- We're here
for Pam Hupp's cell data.

41:00.283 --> 41:03.199
- Not many men can pull off
a pink pocket square.

41:03.243 --> 41:04.549
- Russ started
playing this game

41:04.592 --> 41:06.507
of putting a pillow
over her face.

41:06.551 --> 41:08.509
- Who took Betsy home?
- Her friend, Pam.

41:08.553 --> 41:09.945
- Why don't you
tell me about Pam?

41:09.989 --> 41:11.120
- She's a nice lady.

41:11.164 --> 41:12.426
- [blows loudly]

41:12.470 --> 41:14.297
- I'm gonna make him pay
for what he's done.

41:14.341 --> 41:15.298
- Sheriff's department!

41:15.342 --> 41:16.474
- But...

41:16.517 --> 41:17.475
- Russell Faria,
you're under arrest.

41:17.518 --> 41:19.738
- We need someone
who really knows

41:19.781 --> 41:21.696
Betsy and Russ' relationship.

41:23.829 --> 41:27.528
- Well, I know
everything about it.

41:27.572 --> 41:29.617
- He killed his wife.
- Objection.

41:29.661 --> 41:31.793
- Are you gonna object
to my entire opening statement?

41:31.837 --> 41:33.665
- If you keep saying
objectionable things, yeah.

41:33.708 --> 41:35.057
- [slurping]
- Pamela Hupp lied about

41:35.101 --> 41:36.537
where she was at the time
of the crime.

41:36.581 --> 41:39.148
- All these questions are none
of their business.

41:39.192 --> 41:41.150
- Pamela Hupp is not a suspect.
- Yeah, well, she should be.

41:41.194 --> 41:42.195
- [laughs]

41:42.238 --> 41:44.197
- You're facing life in prison.

41:44.240 --> 41:47.505
- The prosecution calls
Pamela Hupp to the stand.

41:47.548 --> 41:48.984
- I got it from here.

41:49.028 --> 41:51.509
[dramatic music]

41:55.034 --> 41:57.950
[unsettling music]

41:57.993 --> 42:04.913
♪
